<DOC><DOCNO> AP890728-0222 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-28-89 0311EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-28 0747</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0784</SECOND><DATELINE>SMYRNA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Nissan employees voted overwhelminglyagainst being represented by the United Auto Workers, denying theunion a foothold in the nation's fully Japanese-owned auto plants.   Employees voted 1,622 to 711 against the UAW at Nissan's soleU.S. plant, according to results announced Thursday.   The balloting followed an 18-month drive by the UAW and was seenas a test of union muscle and a challenge to automakers' strategyof locating plants in the traditionally anti-union South.   In Tokyo, Nissan management welcomed the union defeat.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Underscoring a consolidation in the drugindustry, Bristol-Myers Co. and Squibb Corp. said they would mergein an $11 billion stock-swap deal that would create the world'ssecond-largest pharmaceutical concern.   Under terms of a definitive agreementapproved by the boards ofboth companies, Squibb will be merged into Bristol-Myers through atax-free exchange of 2.4 shares of Bristol-Myers common stock foreach Squibb share, the companies said Thursday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. economic growth slowed to a lacklusterannual rate of 1.7 percent in the spring while inflation racedahead at the fastest pace in more than six years, the governmentreported.   The Commerce Department said Thursday the gross nationalproduct, the broadest measure of economic health, turned in itsweakest showing since mid-1986 as growth was held back by a slumpin auto sales and housing construction.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chrysler Corp. will retire or lay off 2,300 ofits 31,000 salaried workers by year's end as part of $1 billioncost-cutting program mandated by sagging sales and a changingmarket, Chairman Lee Iacocca said.   The cuts announced Thursday were billed as part of a long-termeffort to make the third-largest U.S. automaker more competitive.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Paramount Communications Inc. completed itstransformation from a conglomerate to a media company, announcingit had sold its financial services arm, The Associates, to FordMotor Co. for $3.35 billion.   Paramount said Thursday the deal would give it an after-tax gainof $1.3 billion. When the company announced plans to sell TheAssociates in April, it said it planned to use the money to financeacquisitions.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Visa cardholders moved closer to the day whena single piece of plastic will enable them to conduct nearly anykind of business, including long-distance calls.   Visa U.S.A and MCI Communications Corp. announced Thursday thatbeginning Oct. 1 Visa card account numbers also will serve as MCIlong-distance calling numbers. Holders of Visa cards will be ableto call from any telephone in the United States to nearly anywherein the world, with monthly charges billed as one line on their Visaaccounts.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Commerce Department said a preliminaryinvestigation showed manufacturers in Japan, Taiwan and South Koreawere ``dumping'' small-business telephone equipment in the UnitedStates at prices far below their fair value.   In a preliminary finding that could lead to hefty antidumpingduties on these phone products, the department's InternationalTrade Administration said Thursday that some Japanese companieswere selling phone equipment in the United States at prices morethan 1{ times below what comparable equipment was selling for inJapan.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   General Motors Corp. said its second quarter netincome dropped 3.9 percent and Ford Motor Co. posted a 15.6 percentquarterly profit decline.   Both companies said the results Thursday reflected a weakeningcar and truck market and the cost of incentives they used inefforts to boost sales, a trend industry analysts had expected.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. said it had firedMcCann-Erickson as the advertising agency for its Winston and Camelcigarette brands in the United States.   The tobacco company, based in Winston-Salem, N.C., said it wasassigning the two brands to two agencies that already handle otherdomestic cigarette advertising assignments for Reynolds, FCB-LeberKatz Partners and Young andamp; Rubicam, both of New York.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices bounded ahead in brisk trading Thursday, as the DowJones average of 30 industrials closed at a new post-crash high of2,635.43, up 22.38 pounts.   Bond prices surged, helped by a government report that showed abig drop in U.S. economic growth.   The dollar ended higher against most major currencies.   Coffee futures prices sank to their lowest level in more than 13years; soybean futures rallied; crude oil futures fell; preciousmetals retreated; and livestock and meat futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>